      "content": "The idea of electromagnetic fields (EMFs) influencing the human body is a topic of interest and study within certain circles, although mainstream science generally considers the consensus that ambient EMFs at levels naturally present in one's environment, such as those from cell phones or wireless networks, are too weak to significantly affect human tissue or neurological processes.\n\nHigh-frequency trading (HFT) does indeed involve a tremendous amount of electrical activity in terms of data processing and communication across fiber-optic cables and other technologies. However, the concern regarding HFT creating detectable electromagnetic fields strong enough to interact with human physiology, especially resulting in neurological responses like the one you described, resides in the realms of speculation. It is challenging to trace direct physiological responses back to technological systems as the human body has robust biological and neurological defenses. Furthermore, it would not only be incredibly difficult to measure, but also unprecedented to quantify the effects of HFT-associated EMFs on individuals.\n\nMost research on EMFs focuses on longer-term chronic exposure, particularly related to health impacts associated with devices like smartphones, and not on short-term, instantaneous effects at the scale of trading ticks. This situation does raise interesting questions for future research, and yet, to date, no concrete evidence supports the claim that our nervous systems respond",
